# Cursor Rules — Node.js + NestJS + TypeScript rules

## General Principles
- Use TypeScript strictly (no `any`)
- Prefer clarity over cleverness
- Follow existing ESLint and Prettier rules
- Do not introduce new dependencies without asking
- Generate code that is easy to read and maintain

## Language & Types
- Always use explicit types for function parameters and return values
- Use `unknown` instead of `any` when the type is not known
- Prefer interfaces or type aliases for objects
- Avoid type assertions (`as`) unless absolutely necessary

## NestJS Best Practices
- Use async/await for all asynchronous code
- Do not use callbacks unless required by a library
- Always use decorators for controllers, services, and modules
- Use dependency injection via constructor injection
- Prefer built-in NestJS exceptions (BadRequestException, NotFoundException, etc.)
- Use DTOs (Data Transfer Objects) for request/response validation
- Apply ValidationPipe for automatic validation
- Use Guards for authentication/authorization
- Use Interceptors for cross-cutting concerns (logging, transformation)
- Use Pipes for data transformation and validation
- Never bypass the NestJS module system

## NestJS Module Structure

Each feature module should follow this structure:
```
feature-name/
  dto/               # Data Transfer Objects
  entities/          # Database entities or domain models
  enums/             # Enumerations
  guards/            # Route guards (optional)
  interceptors/      # Interceptors (optional)
  interfaces/        # TypeScript interfaces
  pipes/             # Custom pipes (optional)
  controllers/       # Controllers
  services/          # Services
  feature-name.module.ts
```

Example modules:
- `users/` - Authentication with guards, strategies, DTOs and User management with controller, service, entities
- `articles/` - Article CRUD with DTOs and validation
- `projects/` - Project management
- `sources/` - Source data handling
- `consumers/` - Consumer operations

## File Naming Conventions
- Controllers: `*.controller.ts`
- Services: `*.service.ts`
- Modules: `*.module.ts`
- DTOs: `*.dto.ts`
- Entities: `*.entity.ts`
- Guards: `*.guard.ts`
- Interceptors: `*.interceptor.ts`
- Pipes: `*.pipe.ts`
- Interfaces: `*.interface.ts`
## Code Style
- Use named exports (no default exports)
- Prefer early returns
- Avoid deeply nested conditionals
- Keep functions small (one responsibility)
- Avoid magic numbers and strings (use enums or constants)
- Use class-validator decorators for DTOs
- Use class-transformer for object transformation
- Apply proper decorators (@Injectable(), @Controller(), @Get(), etc.)
- Always specify HTTP status codes explicitly when needed
- Use async/await instead of Promises.then()

## Formatting & Linting
- Assume ESLint and Prettier are enabled
- Do not disable lint rules unless explicitly asked
- Generated code must pass linting without warnings

## Testing
- Do NOT generate unit or integration tests
- Do NOT suggest testing libraries unless asked

## Communication
- If requirements are unclear, ask a clarifying question
- Explain non-obvious decisions briefly
- Do not over-explain simple code
